what is dependency injection ? Explain
Dependency Injection is a design principle used to build loosely coupled applications. Instead of a class creating the objects it depends on internally using new, those dependencies are created outside the class and passed in — most commonly through the constructor.
In practice, the dependency is usually declared as an interface, not a concrete class. So the class doesn't depend on a specific implementation — it depends on a contract. Any class that implements that interface can be injected, and the dependent class doesn't need to know or care which one it actually got — it just calls the interface's methods, and the correct implementation runs at runtime through polymorphism.
This gives us loose coupling: I can swap implementations, inject mock objects for unit testing, and follow the Single Responsibility and Dependency Inversion principles — since the class depends on an abstraction, not a concrete type

Example 
public interface IEngine
{
    void Start();
}


With DI and an Interface (Loosely Coupled)
public interface IEngine
{
    void Start();
}

Now create implementations:

public class PetrolEngine : IEngine
{
    public void Start() { }
}

public class DieselEngine : IEngine
{
    public void Start() { }
}

public class ElectricEngine : IEngine
{
    public void Start() { }
}
The Car class stays the same:

public class Car
{
    private IEngine engine;

    public Car(IEngine engine)
    {
        this.engine = engine;
    }
}

Now you can do:
Car car1 = new Car(new PetrolEngine());
Car car2 = new Car(new DieselEngine());
Car car3 = new Car(new ElectricEngine());
Notice that the Car class was never modified.
So why is it loosely coupled?
Because Car depends only on the IEngine interface, not on a specific engine implementation.

If you create a new HybridEngine, you don't change Car.
You don't change IEngine either (unless you want to add new methods to the interface).
