what is application lifetime?
When you deploy your ASP.NET Core application to IIS, Azure, Docker, or another server:
The application starts running.
It begins accepting HTTP requests.
This is the start of the application lifetime.
It continues running until:
You stop the application.
You restart the server.
You redeploy a new version.
The application crashes or is recycled by the server.

Then the application lifetime ends.

What is middleware explain it in detail?
Middleware is a software component in ASP.NET Core that is part of the HTTP request pipeline. Every incoming HTTP request passes through middleware before reaching the controller, 
and every outgoing HTTP response also passes through middleware before being sent to the client. Each middleware performs a specific task such as authentication, authorization, logging, 
exception handling, or CORS. After completing its work, it can either pass the request to the next middleware or stop the pipeline and return an appropriate response.

What is filter?
Middleware and Filters both allow us to execute code before and after a request, but they work at different levels. 
Middleware executes for every HTTP request before it reaches the controller and is used for application-wide concerns like authentication, CORS, logging, and exception handling. 
Filters execute only for MVC/Web API controller actions and are used for action-specific concerns such as action logging, model validation, exception handling, and modifying action results.
Middleware doesn't know which controller or action will execute. Filters run after routing has selected the controller and action, so they have access to action arguments, model state, controller context, and action results. 
That's why action-specific logic is implemented with filters rather than middleware
Because Middleware does not know which controller or action is going to execute, whereas Filters do.
We use Middleware for application-level processing and Filters for controller/action-level processing because Filters have access to MVC-specific information that Middleware does not.

What is a Controller?
A Controller is a class in ASP.NET Core that handles incoming HTTP requests, calls the appropriate business logic (through services), and returns an HTTP response to the client.


